{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_iotite_ver01/data/sn84020064/00542866408/1930012401/0001.xml":{"full_text":"Weather\nARIZONA: Generally fair Fri\nday and Saturday; little change in\ntemperature.\nDOUGLAS: The maximum tem\nperature recorded here Thursday\nwas 53 degrees and the minimum\nwas 25\nVOL. XXVII.\nNaval Parity With Great Britain Aim of United States\nMexico Withdraws Legation in Moscow\nCommunist\nActivities\nAre Cause\nAction Is Protest Against\nRecent Demonstrations\nat Embassies.\nSoviet Government Held\nResponsible For \u201cReds\u201d\nEstrada, Minister of For\neign Affairs, Declines\nComment on Case.\nMEXICO CITY, Jan 23 W.\u2014\nThe Mexican government today\n\u2014ordered its entire legation in\nMoscow to leave soviet Russia\nas a protest against the recent\ncommiuist demonstrations be-\nfore the Mexican embassies in\nWashington, Buenos Aires, Ar\ngentina, and Rio Janeiro, Brazil.\nThe Mexican administration holds\nthat the Moscow government was\nresponsible for the demonstrations.\nla Act of Protest\nAnnouncement of the step was\nmade by Genaro Estrada, minister\nof foreign affairs. He revealed\nthat the Mexican minister had been\nordered to leave Moocow several\ndays ago Today the charge d\u2019af\nfaires and all others in the embassy\npersonnel were directed to quit the\n-^tesian capital, \"as an act of pro-\nSenor Estrada, in handing out\nthe written statement to the press,\nmade no mention of the status of\nthe Russian minister to Mexico\nThe statement said that Mexico\ndoes not hold any of the countries\nwhere the demonstrations occurred,\nresponsible for the happenings.\nDeclines Comment\nThe foreign minister refused to\namplify the written notice and\nAlexander Makar, Russian minister,\nalso declined comment of any sort.\nThe statement said that Mexico\nhad tried to maintain friendly re\nlations with Russia, but that the\nlatter had not appreciated this et\nfort. This had produced a situa\nwhich \"it is neither possible\n(Continued on Page Five)\nSeven Arrested\nAfter Race Riot\nBrings Casualty\nFilipino Slain Near Wat*\nsonville, Calif., by the\nWhites; Feeling High.\nWATSONV|ILLE, Cal., Jan. 23 Ori\n\u2014Seven white men were* arrested\nlate today as business men of the\nWatsonville district Joined with of\nficials to put down the race diffi\nculties which reached a climax late\nlast night with the killing of a\nFilipino lettuce picker\nThe seven were charged with\nrioting. One, Fred Majors, was re\nleased under a $2,000 bond, and the\nothers, R. Smith, George Barnes.\nRamon Devls. George Sias. Charles\nMorrison, and Ted Spangei, lodged\nin the county Jail at Salinas.\nTo Hold Inquest.\nThe body of Fermin Tehera, 22,\nfound today shot to death in a\nFilippino bunk house on the Mur\nphy ranch, four miles east of here,\nwas held for a future inquest. No\ndate had been set tonight.\nBy the mayor\u2019s order, all pool\nhalls and such places of amusement\nwere closed at 6 o\u2019clock. Legion-\n(Continued on Page Five)\nWar to Exteminate Bootlegging In\nCapital Launched by Realty Board;\nWill Eject Tenants Who Break I^iw\nWASHINGTON. Jan. 23\nMembers of the Washington real\nestate board have decided to engage\nin a war to exterminate bootlegging\nin the capital\nToday the board decided to strike\na blow at the illicit liquor traffic\nby promising District Attorney Rov\ner to report to him all information\navailable about persons on their\nproperties violating the prohibition\nlaws in that way. with a view to\nobtaining a basis for ejecting them.\nJohn A. Petty, executive secretary\nof the board, announced the de\ncision. It was preceded by confer\nence between District Attorney Rov\ner and officals of the organization,\nwhich comprises most of the real\naOaily\nH>\nIn Poison Case\nM>\nw Jr 'Sr\nHr\n7 f\nL@\nCharged with administering\narsenic to ten cmidren in a\nsummer camp at Montvale, N.\nJ., _ Miss Pearl Topper, above,\na teacher and Columbia univer\nsity graduate, has been indict\ned for \u201catrocious assault\" and\nheld in 550,000 ball. Formerly\nassistant supervisor of me\nsummer camp, she was dis\nmissed after a quarrel with the\ncamp cook. She is alleged then\nto have sought revenge by\nsprinkling arsenic over the\nchildrens\u2019 oatmeal. She has de\nnied the charges.\nFood Dropped By\nPlane to Winter\n\nFlood Sufferers\nHundreds Brought From\nLowlands by Boats; Red\nCross in Charge.\nMEMPHIS, Tenn., Jan. 23\nRelief went by air today to isolated\nregions in the flood-stricken area\nin northeastern Arkansas and the\nsoutheastern tip of Missouri while\nrescue crews battered their way\ninto the ice-bound overflow to\nbring several hundred persons from\nthe flooded lowlands\nAn airplane dispatched from\nMemphis by the Memphis Evening\nAppeal, Joined forces with the\nAmerican Red Cross and dropped\nfood and fuel to distressed low\nland dwellers marooned in cabins\nand isolated farming centers.\nRed Cross Aids\nGround operations were conduct\ned from a base near Blytheville by\nWalter Over, field representative of\nthe Red Cross.\nVolunteer crews of a half hun\ndred men, armed with pick axes,\nmanned boats and nosed their way\ninto the overflow, crushing chan\nnels through the ice.\n\"People in the flooded areas are\nsuffering from cold and some are\nreported 111,\" Mr. Over told the\nAssociated Press, in reporting con\nditions in the flood zone. \u201cIn one\nhouse a rescue crew found some 30\npersons huddled with their supply\nof food narrowed down to some\nmeat.\"\nALTO CRASH FATAL.\nBAKERSFIELD, Cal., Jan. 23 Ori\n\u2014Charles Forties, 43, Fox West\nCoa^4 Theaters construction en\ngineer, was killed and his com\npanion. Charles A. Buckley, an of\nficial of the same organization, was\ninjured near here today when their\nautomobile turned over and struck\na tree.\nestate dealers in the District of Co\nlumbia.\nThese officials accepted Rover's\noffer of assistance in obtaniing wit\nnesses and evidence necessary to se\ncure ejection of Volstead offenders\nfrom hotels, apartments, business\nbuildings and other properties un\nder control of the board. The real\nestate dealers placed at Rover\u2019s dis\nposal their comprehensive records\nof realty transactions, to aid the\ntracing of correct owners of prop\nerties whose occupants are sus\npected of liquor violations.\nThe district attorney said the\npromised co-operation would be of\ngreat value, especially Insofar as the\nboard\u2019s records were concerned. He\n(Continued on Page Five)\nRealty Men\nTold Trade\nWill Revive\nHarry S. Kissell, Who At\ntended Hoover Parley,\nSpeaks at Phoenix.\nDepression Not Serious\nIn U.S.; Needs Cited\nReal Estate Has Passed\nCrisis; Many issues Are\nListed for Discussion.\nPHOENIX. Jan. 23 if*\nCharacterising the recent stock\nmarket collapse as \u201cthe greatest\ncrash of all times,\" and declar\ning there was no cause for \u201cex\ntreme optimism,\u201d Harry 8. Kis\nsell. Springfield, Ohio, first\nvice president of the national\nassociation of real estate boards,\nthis afternoon told delegates\nassembled at the mid-winter\nbusiness meeting of the organi\nzation that only the complete\norganization of American busi\nness could bring about read\nment and a return of prosperity.\nKissell. a featured speaker of the\nopening day\u2019s sessions of the meet\ning, declared there must be a busi\nness recession during the first half\nof 1930. but that no serious busi\nness depression was on the business\nhorizon.\nMaintain Labor\nThe speaker, who attended the re\ncent economics conference called by\nPresident Hoover, Void hw hearers\nthe problem before the businessmen\nof the nation now is to maintain\nemployment at a proper wage, in\norder to enable working men to\nkeep up installments on credit pur\nchases. Credit extension has re\nmoved the danger of overstocking,\na characteristic of American panics,\nthe vice president said.\nNeed Homes\nKissell sounded a warning against\nover-production and the piling up\u201d\nof unsaleable stock at this time and\nstressed the need for the purchase\nof sub-divisions for home building\ninstead of speculation.\n(Continued on Page Five)\nEighteen Racing\nHorses Cremated\nIn New Orleans\nRace Track Fire Costly;\nThree Men Injured in\nRescue Efforts.\nNEW ORLEANS. Jan. 23. Ori\u2014\nFire that destroyed two barns at the\nfair grounds race track at dawn to\nday killed eighteen race horses, two\nlead ponies, and sent three men to\nthe hospital.\nStarting from an exploded oil\nstove, the flames swept swiftly\nthrough the long frame bam, and\nspread to an adjoining barn. The\nfire broke out Just as the stable men\nwere rising for the morning. M^ny\nof the barely awakened men Just\nwere able to stumble to safety.\nShrieks Heard Blocks\nThe shrieks of the horses and the\ncries of men could be heard blocks\naway as desperate efforts were made\nto get the animals out of the bams.\nRescuers had to break in a door\nto save Wilfred May. apprentice\nJockey. J. W. Smith and Phil Chat\nman. stablemen. They were sent to\nthe hospital suffering rrom smoke\nInhalation and burns but were ex\npected to recover.'\nDog Fights Firemen\n\u201cPrince,\u2019\u2019 a large alredalc dog\ntrained to guard the racers at night\nagainst intrusion, mistook the res\ncuers for Invaders and stood off a\ndozen men who attempted to save\nthe horses. He chewed one man on\nthe leg and would not yield, until\nhe had ben stabbed to death with\na pitchfork.\nBig Liner Sinks\nIn Magellan; All\nPassengers Safe\nBUENOS AIRES. Jan. 23.\nThe ministry of marine tonight an\nnounced a dispatch from the naval\nheadquarters at Ushal. Tierra Del\nFuego. stating^ that all the 1.100\npassengers ana the crew of the\nsteamer Monte Cervantes had been\nsaved from the wreck of that Ham\nburg American liner.\nThe ship struck a rock in the\nstraits of Magellan yesterday after\nnoon. \u2019The telegram to the marine\nministry said the steamer would be\na total loss.\nDOUGLAS, ARIZONA, FRIDAY MORNING, JANUARY 24,1930.\nCorrect Boy And Girl\nEvil Is Plea Made At\nRealty Meet By Lawyer\nPHOENIX, Ariz., Jan. 23. Uri\n\u2014Joseph Scott. Los Angeles at\ntorney. received one of the\ngreatest ovations ever accorded\na speaker in Phoenix, as he fin\nished an address beiore the na\ntonal Association of Real\nEstate Boards here today.\nScott told his listeners to \u201cdo\ntheir part to correct the boy and\ngirl evil.\" He said 65,000 boys\nand 10.000 girls were arrested in\nChicago last year, and that most\nof the crimes of today were be\ning committed by \u201cmere youths.\u201d\nNone Responsible\nFor Fatal Plane\nCrash, Says Jury\nFindings Hold Unforseen\nWeather to Blame;Wit\nnesses Testify.\nOCEANCIDE. Cal., Jan. 23 (/P>\u2014\nAdverse weather conditions caused\nthe wreck last Sunday of the\nT.A.T.-Maddux tri-motored airliner,\nthe San Diego county\u2019s coroner\u2019s\nJury found today, after holding an\nall day inquest into the causes of\nthe worst airplane disaster in the\nannals of American aviation his\ntory.\nThe twelve Oceanside rrcechants\nand ranchers returned a verdict\nthat \u201cno one was responsible for\nthe deaths'* of the fourteen pas\nsengers and two pilots who went to\na flaming oblivion on the slope of\na storm-buried Pacific coast bluff.\nHear Eye-Witnesses.\nTestimony of two of the six known\neye-witnesses of th? tragedy\u2014an\nadmittedly emotional woman and\nher husband\u2014was that flames en\nv ?loped the huge craft as it\nplunged to earth with its human\nfreight. Against their description\nwas weighed the words of a four\nteen year old boy, who In clear\nfirm voice testified lie sAw only a\nfive-foot flame beneath the liner's\ncabin and of three other youths who\nraid they saw what might have been\nonly the exhaust fire of the roar\ning motors.\nStories Conflict.\nGordon and Dora Chester. San\nDiego motorists, who were driving\nslowly home through the ram.\ntestified the flames appeared to\nextend from the center motor back\nward to envelope the cabin. Fred\nSims and William Grayson, the\nfourteen-year-old lad and his rum\nble seat companion In the,Chester\ncar. were not sure whether It was\nconsuming flames or merely motor\nexhaust fire they saw as the big\ncraft hurtled over them' into a\nplowed bean field.\nGeorge MacPherson. and Robert\nBethel, sailors, who rushed a report\nof the tragedy to the Oceanside\npolice, said that, although from a\ndistance they had seen the flash of\nthe igniting gasoline tanks, they\ndid not see any fire or any flames\nPlane Fare Cut\nSees Huge Gain\nIn Passengers\nST. LOUIS. Jan. 23 <**>\u2014Previous\nI records for air travel over the\nTrans-Continental Air Transport-\nMaddux lines have been broken\nsince the recent rate reduction\nplacing fares on a parity with rail-\nPullman prices, T. B. Clement, gen\neral traffic manager for T. A. T.\nsaid today. He said 222 revenue pas\nsengers were carried over some por\ntion of the line in the week follow\ning the reduction, although unfav\norable weather caused cancelling of\ntwo days of operation and curtailed\nservice on the other days.\nClement said it was necessary Io\noperate 18 planes in addition to the\nregular 11 in service to care for the\nincreased business. He said 90 to\n95 per cent capacity loads were car\nried during the week.\n\nSEEKS ANNULMENT.\nRENO Nev., Jan. 23 Annul\nment proceedings will be instituted\nhere tomorrow by Mrs. Eugenia\nBankhead Hoyt Butt to have her\nmarriage to Wilfred Lawson Butt,\nex-Ne\\nda football player, set\naside on the ground that Butt had\na wife when they were married\nhere on Dec. 18, last.\n\nRAIL WORKERS KILLED.\nMARTINEZ. Cal., Jan. 23 (A>\u2014\nAndres Olomos, 25, was killed, and\ntwo persons seriously injured this\nafternoon when outhern Pacific\npassenger train No. 56 southbound\nfrom Oakland pier to Los Angeles,\ncrashed into a section crew near\nTormey.\nThe injured were Lui Arriola, 28,\nand Juan Gallo, 22.\nDam Parley\nLimited To\nWater Issue\nAllocation of Power to Be\nLast on Schedule at\nTri-State Conference.\nAll Meetings Secret;\nStatus Of Row Unknown\nPrincipal Fight Between\nCalifornia and Arizona;\nNevada Satisfied.\nRENO, Nev., Jan. 23 Uri.\u2014\nWith the tri-state Colorado\nriver sei vice having reached the\nstage where actaxl propositions\nhave been exchanged, prelimi\nnary negotiations have been\nlimited to the question of allo\ncation of water. As in past ef\nforts to reach a compromise,\nthe division of water as be\ntween California and Arizona\nhas been recognized as the\nknottiest of the problems and\ngiven the first place on the pro\ngram.\nUnder the plan initiated by\nChairman W. J. Donovan, repre\nsentative of President Hoover and\nwho is officiating is mediator, the\nquestion of the allocation of power\nand the price to be charged will\nbe relegated to the background un\ntil It is determined whether there\nis a possibility of Arizona and Cali\nfornia agreeing on the amount of\nwater each state is to receive of\nthe share awarded the lower basin\nstates by the Colorado river com\npact.\nNevada Satisfied\nNevada asked for and received\nfrom the river compact 300,000 acre\nfeet, hence so long as the present\ndiscussions between Arizona and\nCalifornia do not contemplate\nchanging this figure Nevada is dis\ninterested in the water allocation\nnegotiations but will become an\nactive participant in the bargain-\n(Continued on Page Five)\nCoast Publisher\nTo Air Views On\nImmigration Cut\nOpinion Regarding Mex\nico Limitation to Be\nGiven by H. Chandler.\nWASHINGTON. Jan. 23.\nChairman Johnson of the house im\nmigration committee announced to\nnight that Harry Chandler, pub\nlisher of the Los Angeles Times,\nwould appear before his committee\ntomorrow to testify regarding the\nproposal to restrict western hemi\nsphere immigration.\nThe attitude that Chandler would\ntake toward the bill was not an\nnounced. He owns large tracts of\nland on both sides of the border, in\naddition to having large livestock,\nbanking, oil, irrigation and manu\nfacturing enterprises.\nHe will give his views on the ef\nfect that restriction of immigration\nfrom Latin American countries, and\nparticularly from Mexico, would\nhave upon this country, with spe\ncial reference to southern Califor\nnia and the southwest.\nSea Captain Of\nCanada Says LL S.\nBoat Rammed His\nVANCOUVER. B. C., Jan. 23. W\n\u2014Denying that the ramming of his\ndeep sea motorboat Talhaiyp Maru\noff the Mexican coast by the U.\ncoast guard cutter Bonhamlon Jan.\n17 was accidental. Captain J. Butler\nin his report to owners here said his\nvessel was deliberately run down.\nButler said that the Taihciyo\nMaru hove to when the Bonham\ngave chase about 150 miles south of\nthe United States-Mexican border.\nThe cutter rammed the motorboat\nand then drew off. Captain Butler\ndeclared, leaving his command in a\nsinking condition.\nDispatches from San Francisco\nquoted the ooast guard official\nthere as saying the ramming was\naccidental.\n\u201cHELL SHIP\" BURNS.\nSAN FRANCISCO. Jan. 23 UP)\u2014\nThe gallant old barkentine City of\nSydney, once the pride of the Pa\ncific but later known as the \"hell\nship\" of the Alaska fishing trade,\nclosed its colorful career today in\nflames on the Visitacion valley mud\nflats.\nSlays Dry Agents\nI K 189 j\n\u25a0Mr SB Sb js\nK WB i\nWB ii\n>t- 'i.. m Os Is ofi\nhr Ks\nw 1 PM\nBSy\nGeorge Moore of West Palmn Beach, Fla., who shot and killed\ntwo federal prohibition agents when they attempted to search\nhis home for liquor, is shown here with Sheriff Bob Baker. Moore\nis on the right. The slain agents were Robert K. Moncure and\nF. R. Patterson. Their death caused Prohibition Commissioner\nDoran to hasten to West Palm Beach from Washington.\nJury Says Slain\nDry Raiders Were\nMurder Victims\nFlorida Man Who Shot\nTwo Officers Will Be\nHeld for Grand Jury.\nWEST PALM BEACH, Fla., Jan.\n23 </P) \u2014A coroner\u2019s jury, late today\nheld that George W. Moore, alleged\nbootlegger, murdered two federal\nprohibition agents, killed last Sat\nurday when they attempted to\nsearch the Moore home for liquor.\nImahediately after the verdict of\nthe jury, which stated that Rob\nert K. Moncure and F. R. Patter\nson died from gurfcho\u2019. wounds, \u201cin\nflicted by George W. Moore in an\nact of murder,\u201d Justice T. M.\nRick art announced he would issue\na warrant holding Moore for the\ngrand jury.\nThe defense bitterly contested the\ncase throughout the inquest, bring\ning witness after witness in an at\ntempt to prove that the agents had\nattempted an illegal search, after\nnightfall with day time warrants.\nOn the other hand, Jamies S.\nKudlger, and W. M. McNulty, two\nagents who survived the raid, de\nclared it was still daylight when\nthey attempted the search and that\nMoncure first showed the search\nwarrant to Moore (before -askirig\nhim to open up the door.\nGerman Invents\nBoat Material\nFor Many Guns\nBUEREN, Germany, Jan. 23 Ori\u2014\nWhile the delegates to the five\npower naval disarmament confer\nence in London are trying to limit\nor reduce the navies of the world,\na German inventor named Franz\nFelder today demonstrated a new\nmaterial for shipbuilding that is\nclaimed to enable warships to carry\ntwice as many guns as they could\nnormally and to make them prac\ntically unsinkable.\nFelder displayed the buoyance of\nhis patented materials with model\nships. One of them, which was a\nyard long and a foot wide, support\ned a load of 120 pounds, while a\nwood model of the same dimensions\nwent to the bottom of the water\nwith a similar load.\nRemoval Of Tax\nOn Bar Silver\nIn Mexico Asked\nMEXICO CITY. Jan. 23 UP)\u2014Re\nmoval of the government tax on\nproduction of silver is asked in a\npetition to President Portes Gil by\nthe Chihuahua state mining cham\nber, which says such aid is neces\nsary to help the mines in that\nregion out of a difficult situation\ncaused by the drop in me price of\nbar silver.\nThe chamber refers to a decree\nissued by the late President Obre\ngon providing for temporary re\nmoval of the tax when the market\nprice of silver falls below 60 cents\ngold.\nThe price as gone down to 43\ncents, and government assistance is\nneeded to keep the mines running,\nit is claimed.\nSolon Balked In\nMove to Modify\nLeather Tariff\nDemocrat\u2019s Plan Shouted\nDown; Senate Still in\nThroes of Schedule.\nWASHINGTON, Jan. 23 Uri.\u2014An\nattempt to place the senate on\nrecord in favor of tariffs on leather\nand shoes no higher than the \u201ctrue\ncompensatory\u201d levels in event hides\nwere taken from the free list,\nfailed late today and forced post\nponement until tomorrow of a de\ncision of the proposed hide import\nlevies.\nThe move was made by Senator\nSteck, an lowa democrat, who held\nit was unfair to those favoring a\nhide duty to be required to vote on\nthis question separated as it now is\nfrom leather and shoes, and to\n\u201ctake a chance\u201d on getting reason\nable duties on the latter which\nwould not more than offset any\nbenefit from a hide tariff. He\nasked before a final vote that the\ntariff commission be required to\ndetermine the proper levies.\nShouted Down\nAlthough supported in principle\nby Senators Norris, republican in\ndependent, Nebraska, and Dill, dem\nocrat, Washington, the Steck pro\nposal was shouted down easily\nwithout a record vote. Chairman\nSmoot of the finance committee,\nwhose bill proposes duties of 10 per\ncent on hides, from 15 to 20 per\ncent on leathers, and 20 per cent\non shoes\u2014all now on the free list\u2014\ncontended the senate could figure\nout the proper levies itself on\nleathers and shoes if the hide duty\nwere raised.\nVote in Doubt\nThe vote on the proposed hide\nlevy still was in doubt tonight.\nSenator Oddie, republican, Nevada,\nwho had proposed an amendment\nto increase the bill rate to six\ncents a pound on green hides and\n10 cents on cured, modified it when\na vote appeared likely late today\nto the basis of five to nine cents,\nrespectively.\nSenator Walsh, democrat, Mas\nsachusetts, who began the second\nday\u2019s debate today with an asser\ntion that any hide duty would be\nindefensible, also made the prin\n(Continued on Page Five)\nAmerica Appeals to Two Nations In\nEffort to Aid Rear Admiral Byrd;\nIce Threatens Year\u2019s Imprisonment\nWASHINGTON, Jan. 23 UP)\nSwiftly and forcefully, the Ameri\ncan government\u2019s diplomatic re\nsources have been utilized to assure\nthe only possible means of saving\nRear-Admiral Byrd and his Ant\narctic exploration party from a win\nter of bitter privation.\nUnder-Secretary Cotton at the\nstate department late last night or\ndered Minister Swenson at Oslo to\nrequest that the Norwegian govern\nment induce Norwegian whaling\ncompanies to order their staunch\nvessels now in the vicinity of the\nByrd party to undertake the relief.\nAmbassador Dawes at London was\ninstructed to ask the Southern\nWhaling and Sealing company of\nLiverpool to hold their ship, South\nMetal Market\n\u20193k wr quiet; electrolytic, spot and\nJa is. iron quiet; unchanged.\n1 eady; spot and nearby 38.25;\nA 38.75. Lead steady; spot N.\nEast St. Louis 6.10. Zinc\nst Q. East St. Louis spot and fu\ntu. 5.25. Antimony 8.75.\nNumber 179\nDelegates\nAt Parley\nList Needs\nFrance Names Security\nof Europe As Basis of\nNavy Arms Slashes.\nPeace And Economy Are\nListed As Guide By Jap\nFive Power Conference,\nAuspiciously Launched,\nMay Last Weeks.\nLONDON, Jan. 21. (AP)\u2014The\nfive great sea power nations to\nday proclaimed the fundamental\nnature of their naval needs.\nIn Queen Anne\u2019s drawing\nroom at St. James\u2019 palace, and\nunder the eyes of a great por\ntrait of King George the Third,\nSecretary of State Stimson de\nclared that \u201cequality in naval\npower between the United States\nand Great Britain\u201d was the\nbasis of the American position.\nPrime Minister MacDonald plead\ned that the very life of Britain\u2019s\ntiny Isles depended on free and\nopen access to the whole world.\n\u201cOur navy is us,\u201d he said, repeating\nthe formula he had used at the\nopening plenary session of the dis\narmament conference on Tuesday.\nWants Europe Secure\nFor France, Premier Tardieu in\ntimated that everything depends on\nsome arrangement for European se\ncurity. He pointed out that the\nFrench home fleet had to be cut\nInto three parts because France had\ncoast lines on three seas, and added\nthat the French navy must be ade\nquate to \u2018police the trade routes to\nand from the vast. French colonial\npossessions. But, he went on, \u201cif\nthe decisions of this conference re\nsult in an increased sense of secur\nity for France, so much the more\nwill it be possible for France to re\nduct.\u201d\nContinental Parity\nForeign Minister Dino Grandi of\nItaly asserted his country\u2019s claim to\nnaval armament equal to that of\nany other continental European\npower. He said that the conference\nmust consider the problem of se-\n(Continued on Page Five)\nCustoms Officers\nAt Detroit Shoot\nAlleged Rummer\nBorder Patrolmen Defend\nShooting; Victim Not\nExpected to Live.\nDETROIT, Jan. 23 UP).\u2014The\nshooting of a boatman in the De\ntroit river off Wyandotte last night,\nby a customs border patrol inspec\ntor was defended today by the of\nficer and his companion, who\nclaimed the man was attempting to\nland a cargo of liquor.\nThe boatman, Walter Grund, 27,\nwas in Wyandotte General hospital\ntonight with a bullet wound in his\nstomach which was expected to\nprove fatal. He was shot by Clare\nB. Hopper of the border patrol who,\nwith his companion officer, Wil\nliam H. Redford, was awaiting a\nfleet of smugglers\u2019 boats at a wharf\nat the foot of Maple street in\nWyandotte shortly before midnight.\nGrund was found lying in his\nrowboat which had come ashore\nthree miles from the scene. The\nman whom the officers said was in\nthe boat with him had disappeared.\nBefore losing consciousness Grund\ntold Wyandotte police he had no\nliquor.\nHopper and Redford made state\nments to Ward Culver, assistar\nprosecuting attorney, today regard\ning the shooting.\nern Princess, in readiness to assist\nByrd if he shoqld so request.\nIn terse language, Mr. Cotton set\nout that the relief must be under\ntaken at once or the attempt prob\nably would be useless. Otherwise,\nhe said some of the party, at the\nleast, might not live through the\nwirier.\nThe locking in of the winter ice\npacks threatens to isolate the Vir\nginia explorer and his comrades with\ndwindling food supplies.\nThe plight of the party was\nbrought about by abnormal quanti\nties of ice in the pack blocking the\napproch to Little America, the Byrd\nbase. The two ships of the ex\npedition, the City of New York and\n(Continued on Page Five)","height":"26154","width":"20283"}}
